04168nam a22005055i 9780226827384DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226827384  a(DE-B1597)672513  a(OCoLC)1407316024  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aML2551.S58bW66 2023 7aMUS0000002bisacsh04a782.4209677223/eng/202304191 aWoolner, Christina J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLove Songs in Motion :bVoicing Intimacy in Somaliland /cChristina J. Woolner. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b17 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Studies in Ethnomusicology00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tNotes on Language and Terminology -- tCompanion Website -- tPreface: It’s about Love, of Course! -- tIntroduction -- t1. Anatomy of a Love Song -- t2. Lie Down in the Love Hospital (Or, How Love Finds Its Voice) -- t3. Storied Voices, Storied Songs (Or, I Am Calaacal) -- t4. Listening to Love -- t5. Bodies of Music, Instruments of Love -- t6. Staging Love -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tGlossary -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn intimate account of everyday life in Somaliland, explored through an ever-evolving musical genre of love songs. At first listen, both music and talk about love are conspicuously absent from Somaliland’s public soundscapes. The lingering effects of war, the contested place of music in Islam, and gendered norms of emotional expression limit opportunities for making music and sharing personal feelings. But while Christina J. Woolner was researching peacebuilding in Somaliland’s capital, Hargeysa, she kept hearing snippets of songs. Almost all of these, she learned, were about love. In these songs, poets, musicians, and singers collaborate to give voice to personal love aspirations and often painful experiences of love-suffering. Once in circulation, the intimate and heartfelt voices of love songs provide rare and deeply therapeutic opportunities for dareen-wadaag (feeling-sharing). In a region of political instability, these songs also work to powerfully unite listeners on the basis of shared vulnerability, transcending social and political divisions and opening space for a different kind of politics. Taking us from 1950s recordings preserved on dusty cassettes to new releases on YouTube and live performances at Somaliland’s first postwar music venue—where the author herself eventually takes the stage—Woolner offers an account of love songs in motion that reveals the capacity of music to connect people and feelings across time and space, creating new possibilities for relating to oneself and others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLove songsxSocial aspectszSomalia. 0aSongs, SomalixHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  alove songs, voice, multivocality, intimacy, love, sound and affect, love-suffering, Somali music, Somaliland, Hargeysa.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079732940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226827384423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226827384/original  a978-3-11-079732-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles